replies.comment info:
@Tri Nguyen 
Good day Tri.
If you look below the graphs themselves the source line tells us that New York Times staff members visited specific cities. What characteristics of the students sampled might have resulted in homelessness being chosen so often?

@Hadar 
Hello Hadar.
It is very insightful that a 4th grader would chose as the "biggest" problem something that they see often.  But might it be possible that the format of the question itself led to homelessness having such a high percentage of responses?  There appear to be only 8 responses altogether to the "biggest problem" question.  Does this lead you to believe that the question was an open-format-for-response type?  Or is it possible that the question provided specific choices only?

@Izzy Clark AOSE 

Hi Izzy!
Wow.  You picked out something very few people addressed up until now.  How a respondent defines a term (like money) influences whether they choose that term!  What would a fourth grader understand "money" to mean?

@Jack Guldalian 
Hello there Jack!
I noticed that your opinion differs from that of the group.  What characteristic of the sample might make the opinion differ from yours?  Then, is it possible that the format of the question itself produced results that precluded any fourth grader from responding with gun violence as a problem?

@Madeline aose 
Hello Madeline!
Good on you for wondering how the areas where these fourth graders live might affect their responses as well as noting that the amount of emphasis on a topic might influence our opinions on its importance.  Are there other characteristics of how the data was collected that might also influence fourth graders responses?  The source sentence under the graph mentions "visited by New York Times staff."  What might that mean in terms of influence on the responses?

@Samantha AOSE
Hello Samantha,
The graphs themselves do not give us specific indication about where the fourth graders come from.  Fortunately, the source is included just below.  What do the four cities have in common?  How might those common characteristics have influenced why students in those cities responded with homelessness, rather than money?  Based on those characteristics, do you think this sample is representative of the opinions of all fourth-graders?

@Mav 
Good morning to you!
Your "wonder" about homelessness being see as the biggest problem to be solved is spot on.  There are different ways to word a question (open-ended, select from a group of choices, etc.).  Based on the graph, how do you think this question was presented to the students?

@Emily P3 
Good morning Emily,
Your response in #2 to "what do you wonder?" brings up a "wonder" of my own.  Do you think that there is a difference in the opinions of the fourth graders represented in this survey as compared to a group from a decade aga? How much of what is displayed in the graphs can be attributed to how the data was elicited from the students by the journalists?

@Kevin 
Good morning Kevin.
The graphs don't immediately tell us this information, so good on you for digging deeper to notice that the students surveyed were in four specific cities.  How much do you think that the way the responses were gathered affected the results as reflected in the graphs?  We cannot know (because the graphs don't tell us) how the questions were worded.  Based on the graphs themselves, do you think that the questions were open-ended, or did they provide a range of choices from which to select?  How would the results compare using one versus the other?

@Claudia Vieira 
Hello Claudia.
Like you, I wonder about how representative the sample of students is with respect to the population of all fourth graders.  Is there anything else we would need to know about the sample so that the results could be said to represent the opinions of that population?  What about how the data was collected--do you think that makes a difference in our being able to apply the results to all fourth graders?

@Mary R 
Hello to you Mary.
Your "wonder" about how the units a student is studying at the time a survey is taken might influence the responses is spot on.  Given that schools are not in lock step with their curricula, how might this concern be mitigated by the way we obtain our sample?

@Izzie, Eden, Rome 
Hello to the three of you!
Your notice that these fourth graders "have a pretty broad spectrum of the issues that they identified" brings up a wonder of my own.  I wonder if how the question was worded contributed to that spectrum.  Do you think that the question was asked in an open-ended way? Or do you think that the students were presented with a group of selections from which they could choose?  Are there clues in the graph that would give us insight into which was used?

@Kyle Sullivan 

Hello Kyle.
Because the graphs do not say so, you must dig deeper to find out from what places the fourth graders who were surveyed lived.  How do you think this might have influenced 42% of the respondents to pick homelessness as the biggest problem to be solved right now?
